{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474835"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:25:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:25:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12426"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.08,0.15,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4934"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87093"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4934"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71351"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25880"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44124"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87093"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being found collapsed at a party. His friends report he was well until two hours ago when he became increasingly drowsy and confused. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 86/min, blood pressure 82/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 6/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.0\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Scale score is 13/15. He has bilateral pinpoint pupils and intermittent myoclonic jerks. The remainder of his examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following classes of agents most likely explains the history and physical examination findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opioids","Benzodiazepines","Gamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB)","Cannabis","Beta-blockers"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis vignette is characteristic of an opioid overdose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid\u003C/strong\u003E overdose presents as a triad of altered mental status, bilateral miosis, and respiratory depression (manifested by reduced respiratory rate and decreased oxygen saturation). Additionally, myoclonic jerks can occur due to the accumulation of opioid metabolites. Vital signs will show decreased heart rate, blood pressure, respiratory rate, and oxygen saturation. Agents causing this toxidrome include long-acting and short-acting opioids, methadone, buprenorphine, and heroin. This patient exhibits the characteristic signs of opioid overdose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzodiazepine\u003C/strong\u003E overdose would result in features of a sedative/hypnotic toxidrome, which shows the same vital sign abnormalities as an opioid overdose. However, the pupils usually display poor reactivity to light rather than having miosis. Other examination findings include hypotonia, hyporeflexia, sedation, and stupor. Agents causing this toxidrome include alcohol, benzodiazepines, and barbiturates. The presence of miosis and myoclonic jerks points towards an opioid toxidrome in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB)\u003C/strong\u003E overdose is common due to its steep dose-response curve, meaning there is little difference between the amount needed for intoxication and the amount that results in overdose. Overdose is typically characterized by CNS depression, including confusion, agitation, hallucinations, seizures, and blackouts, often accompanied by irregular or shallow breathing. A key feature of GHB toxicity is its rapid and spontaneous recovery, with unconsciousness lasting 1\u20133 hours and full resolution occurring within 4\u20138 hours. Unlike opioids, GHB does not typically cause miosis (pinpoint pupils); instead, pupils are usually normal or dilated. Cardiovascular effects can include fluctuations in heart rate (bradycardia or tachycardia), but due to GHB\u2019s short half-life, sustained hypotension is uncommon. In this case, the presence of bilateral miosis strongly suggests opioid toxicity, as GHB does not cause consistent pupillary constriction. Additionally, the profound respiratory depression (RR 6/min) and significant hypotension (82/60 mmHg) are more consistent with opioid overdose, as GHB-induced respiratory depression is typically irregular rather than severely reduced in rate. While both substances can cause CNS depression, GHB\u2019s short duration of action and the absence of characteristic opioid findings (such as miosis) make it a less likely cause in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecannabis\u003C/strong\u003E overdose usually presents as a psychological disturbance such as depersonalisation, disorientation, agitation, psychosis, and hyperemesis. Examination shows dilated pupils and conjunctival injection, as well as tachycardia and a dry mouth. The patient in this stem shows none of these signs, therefore this option is unlikely. A sympathomimetic toxidrome is characterised by increased temperature, heart rate, and varying blood pressure, along with mydriatic pupils, agitation and confusion, sweating, psychosis, and seizures. Agents causing this toxidrome include cocaine, MDMA, and amphetamines. This patient does not display any signs of a sympathomimetic toxidrome or show any stigmata of a cannabis overdose, making this option very unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-blocker\u003C/strong\u003E overdose results in a sympatholytic toxidrome. This is characterised by vital sign abnormalities such as bradycardia associated with hypotension, conduction abnormalities such as heart blocks and asystole, as well as altered mental status manifesting as lethargy and confusion. Seizures may also occur, which are generally secondary to cardiovascular changes. ECG may show PR, QRS, or QT prolongation as well. This patient does not display any signs of a beta-blocker overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid intoxication presents as a triad of altered mental status, bilateral miosis, and respiratory depression.","Myoclonic jerks can occur in opioid overdose due to the accumulation of opioid metabolites."],"references":["\u0022Toxidromes: A Review\u0022 by Debra A. Pinals and Michael J. Buckley (Journal of Medical Toxicology, 2016) - https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4939580/","UpToDate [Internet]. Bond.edu.au. 2023 [cited 2023 Apr 20]. Available from: https://www-uptodate-com.ezproxy.bond.edu.au/contents/gamma-hydroxybutyrate-ghb-intoxication?search=GHB%20intoxication\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~11\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","\u200cManagement of gamma hydroxybutyrate use [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2023 [cited 2023 Apr 20]. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/january-february/management-of-gamma-hydroxybutyrate","\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71351"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71351"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-25T22:48:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-25T22:49:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4934"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87093"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}}